  "doc_id": "4123",
  "text": "The aberrant pattern of caudate activation in ASD not only supports prior research but also highlights a potentially fundamental difference in how individuals with ASD prioritize CI stimuli over social stimuli. Our finding of greater BOLD responses for CI rewards than social rewards in youth with ASD compared to a more balanced response pattern in TDCs substantiates the earlier report by Dichter and colleagues [CITATION_1] . In contrast to our hypothesis, our follow-up analyses did not reveal specifically diminished caudate responses to social reward when directly comparing the two groups, at least with the social incentives used in this study sample. Other recent functional imaging studies, however, did reveal aberrant caudate responses to both social and monetary reward in ASD [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . Converging evidence from human and nonhuman research links the caudate nucleus directly to decision-making processes, specifically to the selection and initiation of purposeful actions in order to maximize reward outcome [CITATION_4] . In this regard, we found that greater BOLD responses in the left caudate to CI rewards were associated with faster reaction times by the participants with ASD to obtain this positive outcome (but only at an uncorrected significance level). This suggests that in youth with ASD the caudate nucleus may optimize goal-directed actions for CIs to a greater extent than for social rewards or other types of \"conventional\" desires (e.g., money). Whether the caudate nucleus is also involved in aberrant Fig. 4 The magnitude of caudate activation that distinguished the two groups correlated positively with ASD symptom severity as assessed by the SRS-2 social communication and interaction sub-score (for the ASD group only). The stronger the caudate activation for personalized interest reward vs. social reward the greater the social impairment in the ASD group instrumental responsiveness to primary rewards, such as food [CITATION_5] , should be investigated in future studies.",
